[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating testing strategies**\n\nI’m thinking about a one-to-one mapping and adding a TypeUtilTest file instead of Jetty_utilTest. It makes sense to replace certain placeholders with dedicated Java test files and avoid direct reflection in tests, focusing on the TypeUtil API instead. There’s a need to examine lines related to static initialization and JUnit’s coverage tracking. I might also explore whether to use Method.invoke for class2Value with primitives or wrappers to ensure proper coverage. I’m aiming to simplify the approach for method invocations!\n\n**Assessing testing implementations**\n\nI’m considering how to assert that all getMethods are initialized. The getMethod calls in the class initializer don’t need to invoke everything, but must handle wrapper and primitive conversions. I wonder if I should use getConstructor and newInstance with a public class that has a String constructor. There’s the potential to add metadata for the test class, but usually that’s not needed. I’ll need to ensure that native compilation works properly with the reflection configuration for class access. Exploring options, I might use an existing class like java.net.URL for this testing scenario.\n\n**Exploring JDK reflection**\n\nI’m curious about whether JDK reflection metadata is inherently available. Generally, I think it’s not widely supported, but native images may allow for constant folding if the class and arguments are known. Here, using getConstructor with type as a method parameter and passing URL.class as a constant might not be compiled as constant. I wonder if runtime reflection on the JDK’s URL is feasible. I’m leaning toward ensuring a safer approach here while considering my options!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0073ea668cc5e17e0169f4f331710881a1ba00e209c4664c2d\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9PM_Q-h8S4evD0_oS037eQz_NGF